<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Ministry To Push Submarine Program </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2802094894 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 2319 GMT 27 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2802094894 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Berlin (DDP/ADN) -- The Federal Defense Ministry and 
the naval industry are to push ahead with a submarine program 
worth several billion Deutschmarks [DM] before the Bundestag 
election [on 16 October]. That way they want to avoid a 
possible lack of political consensus following a change of 
government in Bonn, the BERLINER ZEITUNG (Monday edition) 
reports. According to the report, the industry will save the 
Defense Ministry quite a few million marks in interest if the 
latter pushes through the procurement of four new U 212-type 
submarines worth DM 2.8 billion before the election. 
  The industry is prepared to bring forward the construction 
work on the four new submarines to 1995, the report says. 
According to a report from the naval arms working group, the 
project was "of such crucial importance" to the industry that 
the industry would be prepared to allow interest-free advance 
financing. In return the Defense Ministry is to yield to the 
industry's demand for "definite plans" that "the project will be 
dealt with in parliament before the Bundestag election on 16 
October 1994." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

