<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   1993 Export Surplus Increases to DM59.4 Billion </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2302152494 Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE in German 
23 Feb 94 p 13 </F>

<F P=103> AU2302152494 </F>
<F P=104>  Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by "J.L.": "Increase in Export Surplus"] </F>
  [Text] Frankfurt, 22 Feb -- The surplus in German exports 
increased strongly again last year. According to the Federal 
Statistical Office, the positive balance amounted to 59.4 
billion German marks [DM] (1992: DM33.7 billion). This was due 
to the fact that imports dropped more strongly than exports. 
While exports decreased by 10.1 percent to DM603.5 billion, 
imports went down 14.7 percent to a level of DM544.1 billion. 
As a result of deficits in the sphere of services and 
transfers, the export surplus was transformed in a deficit of 
DM36 billion (DM39.4 billion) in the balance of payments on 
current account. In December, the export surplus reached DM8.5 
billion (DM0.4 billion), while the deficit in the balance of 
payments on current account was DM0.8 billion (DM4.9 billion). 
Compared to November, exports increased by 4.2 percent to a 
level of DM56.4 billion, thus being 2.2 percent higher than the 
December 1992 level. Imports were up 2.8 percent on the 
previous month, reaching a level of DM47.9 billion, thus 
remaining 12.5 percent below the level of the end of 1992. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

