<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reactions to Fiat Agreement Noted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2402122994 Rome LA REPUBBLICA in Italian 23 Feb 94 p 8 </F>
<F P=103> BR2402122994 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome LA REPUBBLICA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Italian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "From Ciampi to Occhetto: Everyone </F>
is in Favor"] 
  [Text] Rome -- Reactions to the agreement reached on Monday 
night [21 February] between the trade unions, Fiat, and Labor 
Minister Gino Giugni were characterized by a decidedly positive 
tone. For CGIL [Italian General Confederation of Labor] 
Secretary Bruno Trentin, "the Fiat agreement constitutes the 
best which could be achieved, in a situation which is both so 
serious and so full of unknowns, in particular after obtaining, 
at the last moment, the government's formal involvement in an 
extraordinary audit of the company's commitments." However, 
Trentin's reaction is offset by that of the Essere trade union 
in the CGIL which, in a memorandum, contests the agreement. 
  A comment on the solution of the Fiat dispute also came from 
Democratic Party of the Left leader Achille Occhetto, for whom 
"the FIOM [Federation of Employees and Workers in the 
Metallurgical Industry] did a good thing in signing the 
agreement." "The FIOM," he added "has arrived at a new and 
significant position on the question of industrial policies, 
which demonstrates how the real problem today is that of having 
a government and a majority which can have this agreement 
applied as it relates to employment prospects." Prime Minister 
Carlo Azeglio Ciampi, who intervened directly on Monday to 
support a positive outcome of the agreement, yesterday expressed 
to Giugni "the government's appreciation for the intelligent 
work of mediation and for achieving the very important agreement 
in the Fiat dispute." 
  For CISL [Italian Confederation of Trade Unions] Deputy 
Secretary General Raffaele Morese, "this is a victory for worker 
participation." "The agreement reflects," he added, "a fair 
amount of the CISL's philosophy." However, for former CISL 
General Secretary Pierre Carniti, the agreement "is a good 
thing, but the early retirements are the most senseless and 
expensive of all the social shock absorbers." 
  Satisfaction was also expressed by Confindustria [General 
Confederation of Italian Industry] Chairman Luigi Abete. Abete 
described the accord as "a very important result, which 
demonstrates that when the institutions on the one hand and the 
competent social partners on the other hand are allowed to work 
calmly, it is possible to find balanced solutions which address 
labor's problems, but which also give major consideration to 
problems of competitiveness." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-18146 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu039_j_94009" </HT>


