<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Center, Conservative Parties Tied in Poll </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94P20408A Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET in Swedish 10 Feb 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> 94P20408A </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Swedish </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Finnish News Service report: "Social Democrats More </F>
Popular"] 
  [Text] The Social Democratic Party's support is now clearly 
larger than in the parliamentary election of 1991. Conversely, 
the Swedish People's Party has not been able to draw any 
advantage from the popularity of presidential candidate 
Elisabeth Rehn. This is seen from one of the polls that the 
Finnish Broadcasting Company released on Wednesday [9 February]. 
  The Social Democratic Party is now supported by 32.5 percent 
of eligible voters, compared with 22 percent in the 
parliamentary election three years ago. Support for both the 
Center and Conservative Parties is now put at 17.5 percent. In 
1991 almost 25 percent voted for the Center Party and over 19 
percent for the Conservatives. The survey was done by 
Taloustutkimous [marketing research firm] in January-February. A 
total of 1,900 citizens were asked their opinion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

