<F P=101> Sweden </F>
<H3> <TI>   Volvo Seeks To Penetrate Indian Auto Market </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2502112594 Stockholm DAGENS INDUSTRI in Swedish 10 Feb 94 
p 15 </F>

<F P=103> BR2502112594 </F>
<F P=104>  Stockholm DAGENS INDUSTRI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Swedish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Narendra Taneja report: "Volvo Explores Market in India"] </F>
  [Text] Volvo has begun to explore its possibilities in 
India, one of the fastest growing markets in Asia. Top brass 
from Volvo are visiting India from 14 to 17 February in order to 
become familiar with the market and study business opportunities 
in the country. 
  The delegation is led by Nils Arthur, deputy managing 
director of Volvo's Truck International Division. 
  According to an Indian Industry Ministry spokesman, Volvo is 
to study all important areas, from the possibility of 
co-ownership of enterprises to component purchases in the 
country. 
  India has recently opened up the automobile sector to 
foreign 
investors, who can start production without the prior permission 
from the government required in the past. Although the import 
of foreign cars is still limited, it has become easier to get 
lower customs duty rates. 
<H5>  Mercedes Is Already Here </H5>
  So far only Daimler-Benz has begun the assembly of Mercedes 
automobiles at the Tata Engineering and Locomotive Company 
(TELCO) in Pune near Bombay. 
  Manufacturers assessing the studying opportunities offered 
by 
this new market include BMW, General Motors, Renault, Peugeot, 
and Honda. Volvo is represented in India by Modi Motors Private 
Limited. 

</TEXT>

