Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Nikolaos Bellos] </F>
  [Excerpt] Alternate Foreign Minister Theodhoros Pangalos 
said that Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou's letter containing 
the government's political arguments for the measures against 
Skopje [The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia--FYROM] was 
sent this afternoon to European Commission President Jacques 
Delors through diplomatic channels. Pangalos added that the 
memorandum with Greece's legal arguments will be submitted to 
the commission when it is completed. 
  Referring to the possibility of legal proceedings against 
Greece, the European Commission press spokesman clarified that 
the Communal Treaty allows this procedure to be speeded up and 
did not rule out that the court may ask for a temporary lifting 
of the Greek measures. 
  Asked by Greek correspondents, Greek European Union [EU] 
Commissioner Ioannis Palaiokrasas said the procedure of an 
appeal against Greece may be avoided. He said: It is not right 
to end up with such developments. Answering another question, 
Palaiokrasas said the commission has procedures for court 
appeals that are not time consuming. 
  Van Den Broek's spokesman today told reporters that Skopje 
accused Greece of closing its borders even to humanitarian aid. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

