<H3> <TI>   British Foreign Secretary Arrives on Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2702192194 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1800 GMT 27 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2702192194 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd arrived in 
Athens at 1900 tonight on a two-day working visit. In an 
arrival statement, Hurd described the six-month term of the 
Greek European Union [EU] presidency as significant and added 
that he will discuss some issues with Prime Minister Andreas 
Papandreou, Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias, and Defense 
Minister Yerasimos Arsenis. 
  Answering a question on Skopje [The former Yugoslav Republic 
of Macedonia--FYROM], Hurd said a way must be found for the 
dialogue to resume. Asked about the Greek sanctions against 
Skopje and the possibility that they might be lifted, the 
British foreign secretary described Skopje as pregnable, adding 
that it must not be put in danger. 
  Hurd will also meet the opposition leader and other 
personalities. 

