<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cetin Returns From Netherlands, Comments on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2502181794 Ankara Turkiye Radyolari Network in Turkish 
2100 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2502181794 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara Turkiye Radyolari Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Hikmet Cetin has said that Turkey 
insists that the siege in Bosnia-Herzegovina be lifted and the 
six security areas expanded. Cetin also indicated that 
initiatives regarding this issue are under way at the UN 
Security Council. Concluding his two-day official visit to the 
Netherlands, Cetin returned to the country tonight. 
  In a statement he issued at Ankara's Esenboga Airport, Cetin 
said that various issues were discussed and assessed with the 
Dutch officials, adding that he believes this visit will 
contribute to further relations between the two countries. 
  Expressing the concern that unless necessary measures are 
taken against the terrorism perpetrated by the PKK [Workers 
Party of Kurdistan] organization, terrorism could spread to 
other areas in Europe, Cetin stated that the Dutch authorities 
indicated that they are undertaking great efforts regarding both 
terrorism and xenophobia. 
  Noting that in the course of the meetings he pointed out to 
Turkey's determination to join the Customs Union, Cetin noted 
that for a long time now, the EC had not undertaken any 
financial contributions in that direction. Cetin further 
explained that assessments and discussions were conducted with 
the Dutch authorities on alternate ways and means of obtaining 
financial support for Turkey on its joining the Customs Union, 
since the lack of financial assistance on the part of the EC 
meant that the European Unity was not fulfilling its 
requirements toward Turkey. 
  Cetin also pointed out that during the meetings they 
stressed 
the advantages of the integration of Turks into the Netherlands 
community while retaining their cultural identity. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

