<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cetin Receives Slovak Prime Minister </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2502155494 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1435 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA2502155494 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, Feb.25 (A.A) -- Foreign Minister Hikmet 
Cetin said today that Turkey wanted to join the United Nations 
Protection Forces (UNPROFOR) in former Yugoslavia, at least at a 
symbolic level. 
  After his meeting with Slovakian Premier Vladimir Meciar in 
his office, Cetin told reporters that Bosnia-Herzegovina, which 
was the victim of the conflict in the region, had actually 
voiced a request for Turkey's participation in the forces, 
besides the request made by Turkey to Western countries on the 
issue. 
  Cetin recalled that Turkey had been a country which had an 
active stand towards the issue since the beginning and was the 
only country which supported the Bosnians since then. 
  "We spent intensive efforts to bring Croatians and Bosnians 
together and we went to Sarajevo at a time no one had the 
courage to do so. We issued a Sarajevo declaration there. We 
believe, as stated by our premier, Turkey's contributions are 
vital for a lasting peace in the region," he said 

</TEXT>

