<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ciller Meets With Businessmen on Devaluation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2402105094 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1015 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA2402105094 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Istanbul, Feb 24 (A.A) -- Premier Tansu Ciller said 
on Wednesday [25 February] that there was no need to invest in 
foreign currency. 
  Ciller assured businessmen during a meeting held in Istanbul 
that they need not to invest on foreign currency "what we need 
is solidarity and confidence" she added. 
  She said "Turkey could only overcome its economic problems 
by 
being shoulder to shoulder" and called for support from the 
businessmen. 
  Ciller said there was no increase in inflation at the 
moment, 
"the only thing we should do is to increase the entrance of 
foreign exchange." 
  The Central Bank effectively devaluated the Turkish lira by 
nearly 12 percent against the dollar on Wednesday. Turkish 
newspapers, comparing banknote rates, calculated the change at 
13.6 percent. 
  The Turkish lira ended on Thursday at 17,600-700 to the 
dollar after Central Bank intervention above 17,500 restored 
some calm to markets. The Turkish lira was devaluated to 17,250 
on Wednesday night. 
  Exporters, whose goods will become more competitive abroad, 
said short-term cost inflation arising from devaluation could 
nevertheless disrupt industrial production. 

</TEXT>

