<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Expansion Negotiations Continue in Brussels </TI></H3>
<H4>   Talks Suspended, Little Progress Made </H4>
<F P=102> AU2602201094 Paris AFP in English 1950 GMT 26 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2602201094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, Feb 26 (AFP) -- Negotiations to bring 
Austria, Finland, Norway and Sweden into the European Union [EU] 
were suspended on Saturday [26 February] night with little 
progress made in the principal sticking points, EU officials 
said. 
  Norway refused to accept EU proposals over fishing and 
Austria rejected a proposal to relax strict curbs on polluting 
truck traffic across the Austrian Alps, the officials said. 
  The negotiations were due to resume on Sunday. The Greek 
president of the EU's Council of Ministers, Theodoros Pangalos, 
said they faced a make-or-break deadline of Monday midnight. 
  Failure to meet this deadline means that the political 
target 
to bring the four candidates into the Union officially next 
January 1 will probably be missed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

