<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Denmark </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rasmussen on Center Democrats' Support for WEU </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94P20412A Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE SONDAG in Danish 13 
Feb 94 p 7 </F>

<F P=103> 94P20412A </F>
<F P=104>  Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE SONDAG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Danish </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by Bodil Jessen: "Nyrup Denies Conflict on Defense </F>
Policy"] 
  [Text] Toward Election: The Social Democratic Party (SDP) 
is standing fast on the National Compromise, which, among other 
things, says no to joint defense in the Western European Union 
[WEU]. 
  The four government parties are going into the Folketing 
election on their own platforms and will not run on a joint 
program, asserted Prime Minister Poul Nyrup Rasmussen (SDP) 
yesterday [12 February]. Nyrup denied on the same occasion that 
the Center Democrats' [CD] positive stand on the Western 
European Union would be a problem in a future governing 
coalition. 
  This is being said following CD political spokesman Peter 
Duetoft's announcement last week that Danish participation in 
the West European Union should be part of [the program] in a new 
governing coalition. 
  "The Center Democrats have their view, but this will have to 
be dealt with when we know the election outcome," said Rasmussen 
after a meeting between the SDP Folketing group and the party's 
leadership council. 
  At the joint meeting the SDP's European and domestic policy 
goals were adopted. The SDP stands firm on the National 
Compromise and says no to a common defense and a common currency. 
  Regarding the latest cabinet shake-up, Rasmussen said: "The 
leadership council understands the government shake-up of 28 
January. The decision yesterday (the departure of Bente Juncker 
-- BERLINGSKE TIDENDE SONDAG editor) had been under study by the 
leadership council, which was unanimous in the decision." 

</TEXT>

