<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Canada: NATO Attacks `Authorized' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2802220894 Montreal Radio Canada International in English 
2130 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2802220894 </F>
<F P=104>  Montreal Radio Canada International </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Canada supports NATO's decision to shoot down 
four Bosnian Serb planes today. Foreign affairs spokesman 
(Denis Boulet) says the NATO attacks were authorized by United 
Nations Security Council resolutions. Mr. (Boulet) says Canada 
has received no reports of reprisals against peacekeeping troops 
in Bosnia, including more than 800 Canadian soldiers. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-18208 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu040aa_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-040 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 March 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   France's Balladur: `We had No Choice' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2802180494 Paris France-Inter Radio Network in French 1700 
GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2802180494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-Inter Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] For the first time since the beginning of the 
war Western countries have intervened. NATO aircraft shot down 
Serb aircraft that were flying over Banja Luka. [passage 
omitted] Edouard Balladur who was in Toulouse today justified 
NATO's intervention. 
  [Begin Balladur recordings] I believe that we had no choice 
but to enforce the resolutions that had been voted. I believe 
too, that it is time for all the parties involved to understand 
that their common interest is the return to peace in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina and more generally in the whole of the former 
Yugoslavia. This is the policy advocated by France. We are one 
of the foreign countries with the largest number of soldiers on 
the ground and we hope that reason will eventually prevail. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

