<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Western European Union Backs NATO on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0103093794 Paris AFP in English 0229 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0103093794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, March 1 (AFP) -- The Western European Union 
[WEU] on Monday [28 February] backed NATO's action in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina but regretted that Bosnia's Central European 
neighbours had been sidelined in the decision-making which 
mainly involved Washington, Moscow and the UN. 
  The Presidential Committee of the WEU -- the European pillar 
of the Atlantic alliance -- meeting in Paris, praised "NATO's 
resolve" in enforcing the UN-backed no-fly zone over Bosnia and 
the ban on un-policed heavy arms round Sarajevo, according to a 
statement issued after the meeting. 
  However the WEU noted that NATO's 9 February ultimatum to 
withdraw heavy arms threatening Sarajevo or put them under UN 
control "could be implemented only thanks to a tacit agreement 
between Russia and the United States under United Nations 
auspices." 
  But the WEU expressed "regrets" that it was "not possible 
for 
there to be prior consultation with the Central European 
countries whose close cooperation is vital to the conduct of any 
UN policy in former Yugoslavia." 
  The WEU said the "positive development" in Sarajevo should 
encourage efforts to "apply the same policy to other threatened 
areas in Bosnia: Mostar, Srebrenica and Tuzla" amongst others. 
  It said the United Nations Protection Force (UNPROFOR) 
should 
be provided "with sufficient additional troops to enable it to 
carry out its mission of controlling armaments." 
  WEU members and NATO "should make all necessary preparations 
so as to be able to contribute military forces to the 
substantial peace-keeping force that will be required to ensure 
the implementation of a peace agreement in Bosnia-Herzegovina," 
the statement said. 
  The WEU groups France, Belgium, Germany, Greece, Italy, 
Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Portugal, Spain and Britain. 
Denmark and Ireland have observer status. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-18216 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu040aa_94014" </HT>


