<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Italy </F>
<H3> <TI>   Andreatta on Postelection Segni-Berlusconi Alliance </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2802113494 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1329 GMT 26 
Feb 93--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2802113494 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Segni-Berlusconi Alliance Unlikely, </F>
Andreatta Says"] 
  [Text] Udine, 26 Feb (ANSA) -- It is unlikely that Forza 
Italia, led by entrepreneur Silvio Berlusconi, and the Pact for 
Italy of Christian Democratic renegade Mario Segni will be able 
to join the same coalition government after the March 27-28 
elections, according to Foreign Minister Beniamino Andreatta. 
  "The way the election campaign has started," Andreatta said 
on Saturday [26 February] in this northeastern city, "an accord 
between Pact for Italy and Forza Italia after March 28 seems 
very unlikely to me." 
  Andreatta, a former Christian Democrat who is not a member 
of 
parliament, is a Pact for Italy candidate for the Lower House, 
running in the northeastern region of Friuli Venezia Giulia. He 
is running for one of the House seats (25 percent of the total) 
to be assigned using the proportional system. 

</TEXT>

