<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Italy </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Election Campaign Regulations Detailed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2802134894 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1817 GMT 25 
Feb 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2802134894 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Election Campaign Officially Starts, </F>
New Rules"] 
  [Text] Rome, 25 Feb (ANSA) -- The March 27-28 election 
campaign on Friday [25 February] officially took off, with a 
host of new election rules going into effect for the next 30 
days. These are some of the most important among the new rules: 
  As of today, mass media will not be allowed to publish or 
broadcast advertising for parties or candidates but will be 
allowed to announce, broadcast and report on debates, round 
tables, press conferences and speeches, as well as the programs 
of parties and candidates. 
  On Saturday, March 12, (15 days before the polls open), a 
ban 
on the publication or release of any opinion polls or popularity 
ratings will go into effect. 
  An individual campaign spending ceiling of 92 million lire 
(54,700 dollars) has been set for Lower House candidates; the 
spending ceiling for Senate candidates is 115 million lire 
(68,400 dollars). Candidates found to have spent more than twice 
the allotted spending ceiling for their campaigns will face 
removal from office. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-18236 </DOCNO>
