<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to Downing of Planes Over Bosnia Noted </TI></H3>
<H4>   Government Backs Action </H4>
<F P=102> LD2802151294 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1414 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2802151294 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DDP/ADN) -- According to government spokesman 
Dieter Vogel, the four military aircraft shot down by NATO 
combat aircraft over Bosnia-Herzegovina today had "clearly" 
violated the no-fly zone imposed on the country. The four 
planes had been shot at only after two warnings had been given, 
Vogel told journalists in Bonn today. NATO had adhered strictly 
to the UN resolution on the no-fly zone over Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
The shooting down was the "bitter, but necessary" consequence 
of the conduct of the downed pilots and their commanders. The 
federal government was confident that the peace process in the 
former Yugoslavia would not be held up by the incident. 
  A spokesman of the Federal Defense Ministry confirmed that 
German servicemen were also aboard the AWACS reconnaissance 
aircraft that coordinated the NATO operation. At the same time, 
he stated that the deployment of German servicemen on AWACS 
aircraft had been declared constitutional by the Federal 
Constitutional Court in Karlsruhe. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

