<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister, Counterpart Discuss Cyprus </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2202082194 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 0530 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2202082194 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Speaking after meeting Cypriot Foreign Minister 
Alekos Mikhailidhis in Bonn, German Foreign Minister Klaus 
Kinkel said he cannot make promises on a solution to the Cyprus 
problem because they would be empty. He said that as the German 
foreign minister, he cannot resolve the problem alone. The only 
thing he can do, he said, is support Cyprus in every way and try 
to help. 
  The German foreign minister said that in every talk he has 
with the Turkish friends, as he referred to them, he raises the 
Cyprus issue. He added, however, that he is in no position to 
dictate a solution to the Turkish side. 
  Referring to the effect that the promotion of Cyprus' 
European Union membership application will have on a solution, 
Kinkel said he understands the Cypriot position but said he is 
reserved and careful. He added that he will raise the issue in 
Brussels. 
  Mikhailidhis said he was satisfied with his meeting with 
Kinkel, although no definite answers were given. Mikhailidhis 
will meet former German Foreign Minister Hans Dietrich Genscher 
today. 

</TEXT>

