<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-040 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Location of Russian Ammunition Unclear </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2102174694 Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE in German 
21 Feb 94 p 2 </F>

<F P=103> AU2102174694 </F>
<F P=104>  Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by "fy": "Ammunition `Probably Never Existed'"] </F>
  [Text] Hamburg, 20 Feb -- The Federal Government 
apparently does not intend to urge the Western Group of Russian 
Armed Forces in Germany (WGT) or the Russian Government to 
quickly clarify the whereabouts of 81,000 tonnes of ammunition, 
which is still stored in the Russian ammunition depots in the 
new laender, according to the Russian Armed Forces. Upon an 
inquiry, the Foreign Ministry expressed the suspicion that the 
ammunition in question "probably" never existed -- at least, it 
was "probably not" stored in the depots of the Russian Army in 
Germany. Also, it is considered completely "unlikely" that it 
was buried on the vast training area. Questions as to whether 
the government wants to know exactly what happened with the 
ammunition have been answered evasively. 
  In the Finance Ministry, which is responsible for the 
property returned by the Russians, the report gave rise to fears 
that the new laender might refuse to assume responsibility for 
the property. The laender do not want the risk of taking back 
land contaminated by ammunition and, thus, be responsible for 
the disposal of toxic waste. The leadership of the Defense 
Ministry has issued a decree forbidding the passing on of 
information to the public about problems resulting from the 
ammunition and about violations of existing agreements that 
might be discovered in the future. In addition, the Bundeswehr 
is not allowed to approach the Western Group of Russian Armed 
Forces -- as in the past -- if deviations from existing 
agreements are noticed. This is the exclusive task of the 
Foreign Ministry. 

</TEXT>

