<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Neo-Nazi Groups To Support Republikaner </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2102174494 Hamburg DER SPIEGEL in German 21 Feb 94 p 17 </F>
<F P=103> AU2102174494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DER SPIEGEL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Help From Neo-Nazis"] </F>
  [Text] Neo-Nazi groups want to support the right-wing 
extremist Republikaner in the Bundestag elections. At a meeting 
in Saxony, leading members of two banned neo-Nazi parties, the 
German Alternative and the National Offensive, decided to 
establish an electors' initiative for the Republikaner together 
with the Hamburg National List, which is facing a possible ban 
by the Federal Constitutional Court. According to Christian 
Worch, leader of the National List, the neo-Nazis are "grimly 
determined" to "make important impacts" on the election 
campaign. The Republikaner, who are careful to disassociate 
themselves from the neo-Nazi scene in the public's eye, have 
threatened to take legal action against the unwanted neo-Nazi 
helpers. This does not trouble Worch: "Legally, Schoenhuber is 
completely powerless against demonstrations of sympathy." 

</TEXT>

