<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Report on Farewell Interview With President </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2802211294 Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network in Finnish 
1700 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2802211294 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Finnish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] President Mauno Koivisto thinks that at the time of 
changing presidents, Finland is not in such a period of 
transition where a change of guard will cause problems. 
Koivisto did not think that he had left unfinished any projects 
that would have strongly depended on him. The only matter that 
had intensified at the time of the transfer of power was the 
negotiations for European Union membership. President Koivisto 
thought now, before the decisive talks, that they had proceeded 
a long way and the number of open issues have been reduced. In 
his opinion, it looks very much as if Finland has the least 
number of open issues after Sweden. It is possible that a 
solution will be found. 
  In a farewell interview granted for the Finnish News Agency 
at Maentyniemi [new presidential residence in Helsinki], 
Koivisto thought that new President Martti Ahtisaari will handle 
matters in the traditional matter. The president will devote 
himself to international issues. 

</TEXT>

