<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU `Somewhat Closer' to Demands on Farming </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2802213494 Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network in Finnish 
1900 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2802213494 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Finnish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] The European Union [EU] has come somewhat closer 
to Finland's demands concerning farming. Foreign Trade Minister 
Pertti Salolainen in Brussels ponders in the following remarks 
whether a negotiation result will be achieved on the basis of 
the new offer during the night: 
  [Begin Salolainen recording] Well, that depends entirely on 
whether we will get our central views accepted. As has been 
noted, this document is not acceptable to us as it is; there 
must be considerable improvements made to it. We are currently 
deliberating them among ourselves and preparing our own 
counterproposals. That will indicate whether a solution can be 
found. [end recording] [passage omitted] 
  Foreign Minister Heikki Haavisto is, however, still 
dissatisfied. 
  [Begin Haavisto recording] There are numerous points. Of 
course, the two most central ones are that we must get the 
subsidy arrangement to extend to all of Finland and, secondly, 
that the arrangements for the transition period must be such 
that they do not cause unreasonable problems for any sector in 
Finland. [end recording] 
  The Finnish Government will meet in an hour to study the 
situation in the EU negotiations, i.e., a couple of hours before 
the original deadline. Prime Minister Esko Aho thinks that 
there is, if necessary, a margin of flexibility in the timetable. 

</TEXT>

