<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to U.S. Downing of Four Serb Aircraft </TI></H3>
<H4>   Italy's Andreatta Justifies Downing </H4>
<F P=102> BR0103090494 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1931 GMT 28 
Feb 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0103090494 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "NATO/Bosnia: Andreatta on Air </F>
Strike"] 
  [Text] Brussels, 28 Feb (ANSA) -- Italian Foreign Minister 
Beniamino Andreatta, commenting on the downing today by NATO 
fighters of four planes over Bosnia, said that "It seems obvious 
to me that once a rule is set down, it is to be applied." 
  Speaking to journalists on the sidelines of a marathon 
negotiating session underway here since Friday [25 February] to 
enlarge the European Union to include Austria, Finland, Norway 
and Sweden, Andreatta noted that a full report on the episode 
has not yet been compiled and that, until then, a final 
judgement could not be made. "What is certain, is that the 
planes violated the UN resolution banning military flights over 
Bosnia," he went on. If these planes were also involved in an 
attack, then the NATO intervention would have "even further 
justification," he added. 
  Andreatta said that the pilots of the American jets had 
requested and received from their commanders authorization to 
open fire. 
  The Italian foreign minister also pointed out that planes 
like those downed today were at the disposition of Croats, Serbs 
and Bosnian Serbs and that, as a result, the situation was still 
"a bit confused." 
  Ever since UN decreed the no-fly zone over Bosnia, there 
have 
been hundreds of violations, he added, noting however, that it 
was mostly helicopters that had invaded the banned airspace. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

