<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Papoulias-Hurd Discussion </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2802211094 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1800 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2802211094 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The downing of four aircraft in Bosnia has sparked 
strong concern and feverish consultations in Athens. Naturally, 
the issue arose during UK Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd's 
contacts and talks with Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias, the 
prime minister, and the official opposition leader Miltiadhis 
Evert. 
  Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou is being constantly 
briefed 
on the developments and the Greek Government maintains an open 
line with Moscow, Belgrade, and Zagreb with the aim of averting 
suspension of the peace talks. Both Mr. Papoulias and his 
British counterpart Douglas Hurd expressed hope that today's 
incident will not hinder the peace process. The following 
report by our correspondent Foivos Kardhis gives the details on 
the British foreign secretary's visit: 
  [Begin recording] [Kardhis] The dogfight in Bosnia raised 
strong concerns in Athens and with Foreign Minister Karolos 
Papoulias and his British counterpart Douglas Hurd, who met 
shortly afterward and expressed hope that it would not become an 
unexpected obstacle to the peace process. Mr. Papoulias and Mr. 
Hurd immediately had telephone conversations with Russian Deputy 
Foreign Minister Vitaliy Churkin and at noon with Foreign 
Minister Andrey Kozyrev. This open line with Moscow stresses 
the West's conviction that this time as well Russia will have a 
decisive role in averting a new crisis. 
  Mr. Papoulias contacted the prime minister twice to convey 
to 
him the latest reports from Bosnia and NATO Headquarters in 
Brussels. 
  Mr. Hurd asserted in a harsh tone that the Atlantic alliance 
is implementing a policy that was already decided upon and will 
do the same in the future, whereas at his news conference he 
noted that the aircraft were shot down because unlike former 
violations of the no-fly zones, which were isolated, this time 
the operation involved a whole formation. 
  However, nobody aims at a new escalation of tensions in 
Bosnia a few days after the decision of [words indistinct] 
military involvement by the West with the expiration of the 
ultimatum on Sarajevo. 
  [Papoulias] It is our joint conviction that, no matter how 
unpleasant and difficult what happened is, it cannot revoke the 
[words indistinct] peace process. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

