<H3> <TI>   Ruehe: Somalia Mission Cost DM310 Million </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2802132094 Hamburg DPA in German 0937 GMT 28 Feb 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2802132094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Bonn (DPA) -- The Bundeswehr mission in Somalia 
has cost some 310 million German marks [DM], DM240 million of 
which will have to be paid by the German taxpayer, while DM70 
million will be refunded by the United Nations. Material worth 
DM60 million, including, for example, a field hospital and 
communications equipment, can be used in the future, too, and 
has, thus, to be regarded as "long-term investment." This was 
stated by Defense Minister Volker Ruehe, of the Christian 
Democratic Union [CDU], in Bonn on Monday [28 February]. The 
budget funds used by the Bundeswehr in Somalia are an 
"investment in humanitarianism and the future of the 
Bundeswehr," the minister stressed. 
  According to Ruehe, the mission of the German Armed Forces 
within the framework of the United Nations saved tens of 
thousands of people from sure starvation and illness. "The 
commitment of our soldiers was an act of humanitarianism, which, 
due to the special conditions in Somalia, could only have been 
provided by soldiers," Ruehe said. The funds used for it are 
"an investment in humanitarianism." 
  The largest single amount (DM102 million) of the almost 
10-month mission of a total of approximately 3,000 German blue 
helmets, which started in May 1993, went to transportation. Of 
that, a total of DM48.5 million was spent on civilian transport, 
above all charter flights. The military transports cost DM53.5 
million. [passage omitted] 
  According to a paper issued by the Defense Ministry, the 
United Nations already last year transferred DM13.4 million of 
the total refund of DM70 million. 

</TEXT>

