<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ciampi To Quit Politics After General Election </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2802111794 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1827 GMT 26 
Feb 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2802111794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Ciampi Hopes for New Premier Chosen </F>
From Parliament"] 
  [Text] Trieste, 26 Feb (ANSA) -- Prime Minister Carlo 
Azeglio Ciampi, Italy's first government chief who is neither a 
member of parliament nor a card-carrying party member, on 
Saturday [26 February] said he hoped the next government will be 
led by a member of parliament, as proof that the country's 
delicate moment of transition is past. 
  "I hope that the return of the prime minister's post to an 
elected member of parliament, considering the Italian tradition, 
will be seen as a positive sign for Italy, a signal that Italy 
is returning to normalcy and ending a critical phase," Ciampi 
said. 
  Ciampi, a former central bank governor, has been in a 
caretaker position ever since he tendered his resignation on 
January 13. He is not running in the March 27-28 elections and 
intends to withdraw from politics after his present government 
is sent home, presumably after the new parliament takes office 
on April 15. 
  "I was personally involved in this government because this 
transition was seen as best carried out by a non-parliament 
member," he said, referring to the decision by President Oscar 
Luigi Scalfaro to give Ciampi a mandate in April of last year. 
  Italy over the last two years has been caught up in 
burgeoning corruption scandals, which decimated the traditional 
parties, discredited many members of parliament and initiated 
widespread calls for voting and institutional reforms. A spate 
of car bombings in the spring and early summer of last year, 
combined with two rounds of local elections, deepening recession 
and the birth or mutation of many political parties, all added 
to growing political uncertainty. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

