<F P=100> AUSTRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Enterprises Set Up 500 Joint Ventures With Poland </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0203102794 Salzburg SALZBURGER NACHRICHTEN in German 2 Feb 
94 p 9 </F>

<F P=103> AU0203102794 </F>
<F P=104>  Salzburg SALZBURGER NACHRICHTEN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["SN, APA"-initialed report: "500 Joint Ventures With </F>
Poland; Austria Invests 1.5 Billion Schillings"] 
  [Text] Austrian enterprises have concluded some 500 joint 
ventures with Polish partners. The entire investment amounts to 
1.5 billion schillings, making Austria one of the most important 
investors in Poland. 
  The strongest Austrian commitment has been in the 
construction sector. Yet, Austria is also represented in the 
trade, consulting, and the banking sectors. "Austrian companies 
should invest more in Poland now," trade delegate Rudolf Orisich 
recommended at a seminar in Vienna. He emphasized that Poland 
could boast the best economic figures in East Europe. GDP has 
increased by 4.5 percent, industrial production by 7 percent, 
the agricultural sector by 1.5 percent, and private consumption 
by 9 percent (estimated figures for 1993). At the moment, some 
40 percent of the economy has been privatized, and a third of 
industry, 50 percent of foreign trade, and 90 percent of retail 
trade has been denationalized. 
  In 1993, Austrian exports decreased by 8.8 percent to 6.4 
billion schillings, while imports fell by 6.6 percent to 4.7 
billion schillings. The agreement between Poland and the 
European Free Trade Association is intended to stimulate 
relations. 

</TEXT>

