<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Communist Renewal Condemns Air Strike; League Approves </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0103140994 Rome LA REPUBBLICA in Italian 1 Mar 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> BR0103140994 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome LA REPUBBLICA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Italian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Communist Renewal Utterly Condemns </F>
Action, League Welcomes It"] 
  [Text] Rome -- Communist Renewal harshly condemned the 
downing of four Serbian aircraft in the Bosnian "no-fly zone," 
whereas the League welcomed the news. "This action may 
shipwreck the fragile truce which is currently under way," 
Communist Renewal stated. "We are asking ourselves what NATO's 
true motives might be. Having been forced to renounce the 
implementation of the ultimatum as a result of Russia's 
intervention, NATO now seems to be looking for other pretexts to 
address the issue once again in military rather than in 
diplomatic terms." The Northern League did not share this 
opinion: "This is the first time that the violation of a 
cease-fire imposed by the United Nations in Bosnia has been 
penalized, and this is undoubtedly a positive fact. NATO's role 
in the Bosnian conflict is confirming how essential NATO is for 
European security, contrary to what certain political forces 
within the so-called progressive alignment are saying." 

</TEXT>

