<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Berlusconi Responds to Bossi Attacks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0103205094 Rome RAI Due Television Network in Italian 1845 
GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0103205094 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome RAI Due Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Italian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Forza Italia leader Silvio Berlusconi by </F>
unidentified reporter; place and date not given--recorded] 
  [Text] [Announcer] How does Silvio Berlusconi answer the 
attacks made by his ally [Northern League leader] Umberto Bossi? 
  [Bossi] Ours is a great idea, a strong idea, a great project 
to give Italy a liberal-democratic majority and government. I 
believe that this idea is so strong that it cannot fail but to 
advance confidently. It is stronger than protagonists and men, 
and perhaps stronger even than their particular positions -- and 
why not? -- than their egoism and their tawdriness. 
  [Reporter] So you see Bossi and [National Alliance leader 
Gianfranco] Fini coming together again? 
  [Berlusconi] I see a project that will win. 
  [Reporter] All the political forces want to name the prime 
minister. Does Forza Italia also want its own prime minister? 
  [Berlusconi] No, I believe that Italians will choose a prime 
minister with their votes. If, as I forecast looking at today's 
opinion polls, the freedom alignment or the group for good 
government -- that is, the liberal-democratic group -- will win. 
The votes obtained within this group will indicate who should 
be given the task of forming a government. 

</TEXT>

