<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reaction to Downing of Aircraft Over Bosnia </TI></H3>
<H4>   Commentary Views Attack </H4>
<F P=102> AU0103144094 Berlin DIE WELT in German 1 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU0103144094 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Martin S. Lambeck commentary: "NATO's Response"] </F>
  [Text] By downing four Serb combat aircraft, the Western 
alliance addressed the right signal to the Serbs. The intruders 
had been asked several times to turn away from the no-fly zone. 
They did, however, not take the combat planes seriously, just 
as the Western alliance has often been ridiculed over the past 
weeks. 
  This might have changed since yesterday's downings: The 
Bosnian Serbs know now that NATO means business. The fact that 
in this first NATO air strike on Bosnia, the AWACS planes had 
German crew members on board has answered all questions as to 
what would happen if German staff were on board radar 
reconnaissance planes in a similar case. They helped enforce UN 
Resolution 816 in a NATO military strike. 
  Thus, there is hope that all warring parties in Bosnia have 
realized that the international community will no longer watch 
the killing and blocking of aid without taking action. What 
will have to follow is an active policy of humanitarian aid on 
the part of the United Nations. 
  The time has now come to get aid convoys for the starving 
population on their way. And they will have to be forced 
through, if necessary. This is the only way the international 
community and NATO can take the initiative in hand. And this 
would be the first step on the way to achieving tangible results. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-18358 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu041_h_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-041 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  2 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bonn Views Involvement in Bosnia Reconstruction </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0103164694 Berlin DIE WELT in German 1 Mar 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> AU0103164694 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Martin S. Lambeck report: "Bonn Considering Involvement"] </F>
  [Text] Bonn -- The Federal Government is considering ways 
to become involved in the peace process in Bosnia. Although the 
Chancellor's Office denied reports that it was planning to send 
Bundeswehr medical staff and pioneers to Mostar, Chancellor Kohl 
said that for Bosnia one would "go to the bounds of possibility." 
  The Chancellor expressly promised logistic help for the NATO 
countries involved in the peacekeeping operations, if this is 
required. This would involve air lifts and logistic measures in 
Italy and the Adriatic. 
  In Bosnia itself, civilian relief organizations might become 
active. Together with the idea of having Mostar, besieged by 
the Croats, administrated by a German, plans have been published 
that Bundeswehr medical officers are to put the local hospital 
in order and German pioneers are to repair roads and bridges. 
  On these allegations, the Chancellor's Office says: "We do 
not have any such plans." The prompt denial has a good reason: 
Defense Minister Volker Ruehe and government experts are afraid 
of a Serbian hunt for German helpers in Bosnia. "Only officials 
at conference tables could plan something like that," the 
Chancellor's Office said -- a discreet dig at the Foreign 
Ministry. 
  After all, the Defense Ministry also has a plan for German 
soldiers to be made available in the former Yugoslavia: Once 
the peace process is finally under way and no more shots are 
fired in Bosnia, Volker Ruehe might consider establishing a 
field hospital in Croatia where the injured could be treated and 
UN peacekeeping troops supplied. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

