<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Visit by Hungarian Prime Minister Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   Confirms Bosnia Sanctions </H4>
<F P=102> LD0103225894 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
2200 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0103225894 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hungarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hungary intends to submit its application for EU 
[European Union] membership in April, with parliament's 
approval, Prime Minister Peter Boross said in Bonn. In the 
second half of the year Germany, as the president of the EU at 
the time, will put the extension of the organization on the 
agenda. Chancellor Kohl considers it a wise decision that 
Hungary wants to submit its application to the EU already in the 
first half of the year. Helmut Kohl met the press after having 
a two-hour discussion with Prime Minister Peter Boross in Bonn. 
  The Hungarian prime minister rules out the possibility of 
any 
conflict similar to the one in the former Yugoslavia evolving 
between Hungary and its neighbors because of the nationalities. 
Peter Boross pointed out in Bonn that Hungary observed the UN 
sanctions against Yugoslavia despite the fact that it had so far 
suffered a loss of 1.5 billion dollars because of them, and it 
still could not see greater international willingness for 
compensation. 

</TEXT>

