<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Berlin Couple Charged With Spying for Stasi </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0203120294 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1051 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0203120294 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Karlsruhe (DDP/ADN) -- The former Berlin SPD [Social 
Democratic Party of Germany] deputy Bodo Thomas and his wife, 
Helga, who has been an SPD member at Berlin's house of deputies 
since 1989, have been charged with spying for the former GDR. 
The federal prosecutor's office said in Karlsruhe today that 
the 62-year-old Bodo Thomas, who was a member of the house of 
deputies between 1971 and 1989, supplied the Ministry for State 
Security (MfS) with information from the Berlin parliament and 
SPD sources. Thomas was an SPD specialist in matters concerning 
Germany and Berlin. His wife, whose immunity as a deputy was 
lifted last year, is alleged to have helped Thomas and covered 
for him. Both accused, who deny the allegations against them, 
are at liberty, the office said. 

</TEXT>

