<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Former GDR Spy Johanna Olbrich Jailed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2502100994 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 0840 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2502100994 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Duesseldorf (DDP/ADN) -- The Duesseldorf Higher 
Regional Court today sentenced former GDR spy Johanna Olbrich to 
two years, six months imprisonment for secret service activity. 
Frau Olbrich worked for the FDP [Free Democratic Party] in 
various posts, and spied on the party for the former GDR for 16 
years until 1985, under the codename Sonja Lueneburg. She 
worked, among other things, for Martin Bangemann, the former 
German economics minister and present EC Commissioner. 
  Before the verdict was pronounced, Frau Olbrich said she 
expected to get a prison sentence. "Those who get involved in 
work of this nature have to take the consequences," she told 
journalists with obvious calm. 

</TEXT>

