<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Experts Fear New Narcotics Wave Hitting Berlin </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2502142894 Berlin BERLINER ZEITUNG in German 22 Feb 94 p 16 </F>
<F P=103> AU2502142894 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin BERLINER ZEITUNG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by "ls": "Is Berlin Facing a Narcotics Wave?"] </F>
  [Excerpt] [Passage omitted] Police experts see a new wave 
of drugs approaching the German capital. So far, there have 
been 8,000 to 9,000 heroin or cocaine addicts in Berlin, 
according to official estimates. Says an investigator: "I am 
sure that in the future the large East European dealers will use 
the distribution network for illegal cigarettes to sell hard 
drugs." 
  There is also a new route for smuggling drugs into the 
capital -- the West African route. The drugs come from Ghana 
via Zurich to Berlin. Since the end of last year the drug 
investigators have been watching this trend. The drug couriers 
swallow condoms filled with drugs, so-called containers. Then 
they fly to Europe and report to their contacts. At the end of 
1993 alone the investigators caught four couriers from Ghana 
with forged passports. According to findings by the criminal 
police, the hot goods are partly produced in West Africa. 
However, South American cartels, too, use Ghana as an interim 
storage site for transports to Germany. Behind the African 
gangs of smugglers there are mostly old tribal ties with a 
strict hierarchy and their own language. Last year Berlin drug 
investigators seized 15 kg of heroin and 35 kg of cocaine. In 
1992 they caught 12.3 kg of heroin and 26.5 kg of cocaine. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

