<F P=100> SPAIN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vargas: NATO Attack on Aircraft `Was Expected' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0103195994 Madrid RNE International in Spanish 1400 GMT 1 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0103195994 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid RNE International </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Spanish Defense Minister Julian Garcia Vargas 
believes that the allied attack on aircraft of the former 
Yugoslavia does not place the Spanish blue helmets in particular 
danger, because more tense situations have been experienced, 
such as the one last week when the Western ultimatum expired. 
  In statements in the Congress lobby prior to reporting to a 
closed session on the operational situation of the Armed Forces, 
the minister explained that it is still not known to which force 
the downed aircraft belonged because noone is owning up to it. 
For this reason, an increase in tension is not expected. 
  Garcia Vargas considers that, in a sense, the attack was 
expected because it has always been thought, he said, that the 
violation of the air exclusion zone should elicit a response. 
Yesterday saw the materialization of a possibility that had 
always existed. 
  He also referred to the possibility of mortar attacks on 
Sarajevo. If this shelling is continuous, he said, there will 
be a NATO attack. 

</TEXT>

