<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Leaves for Middle East Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0103132694 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1230 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0103132694 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias described his 
tour of Middle East countries, which began this morning, as 
difficult but very significant. Tunis is the first stop on the 
tour. 
  In a statement shortly before leaving for the Tunisian 
capital, the Greek foreign minister stressed that the European 
Union [EU] and the Greek Presidency's presence in the Middle 
East may contribute at this crucial time. He added: An effort 
will be made so as not to lose everything that has been achieved 
toward a permanent, peaceful solution to the Middle East problem. 
  The foreign minister is visiting the Middle East in his 
capacity as the president of the EU Council of Foreign 
Ministers. EU Commissioner Hans Van Den Broek is accompanying 
him. 
  Today, the foreign minister will meet the Tunisian president 
and foreign minister as well as PLO leader Yasir 'Arafat. 
Tomorrow, Papoulias will go to Jordan for talks with King 
Husayn. On Thursday [3 March], he will go to Israel for talks 
with Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin, Israeli Foreign 
Minister Shim'on Peres, and Palestinian representatives. On 
Friday, the foreign minister will visit Egypt for talks with 
Egyptian President Husni Mubarak and the secretary general of 
the Arab League. In his talks with his counterparts and 
political leaders in each country, Papoulias will review 
bilateral relations. 

</TEXT>

