<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Ambassador Proposes Regional Common Market </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0203113194 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 0955 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA0203113194 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, March 2 (A.A) -- Russian Ambassador to 
Ankara Albert Chernyshev said on Tuesday [2 March] that a common 
market could be established in the region. 
  Chernyshev, who was in Ankara for six and a half years as 
ambassador, hosted a farewell reception before his departure to 
his country, where he was appointed as deputy foreign minister. 
  After a one-hour meeting with President Suleyman Demirel, 
Chernyshev told journalists that he and Demirel exchanged views 
on almost every subject. 
  "Strong friendly relations are necessary in the region to 
overcome problems," he said. 
  Chernyshev, who expressed his emotions of leaving Turkey, as 
"my heart will stay here," will be responsible of an area 
covering the Black Sea, the Caucasus, Central Asia, Turkey, 
Iraq, Iran, Afghanistan, Pakistan, India and the Maldives. 
  He said that no other country was welcoming either Turkey 
and 
Russia to sell their goods and "here is our great market, we 
have this opportunity and we should work in this direction." 
  "We are obliged to cooperate. Peace and stability should 
exist here," he concluded. 

</TEXT>

