<DATE1>  2 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister on Initiatives for Palestinians' Security </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0103165394 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1605 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA0103165394 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, Mar. 1 (AA) -- Labor and Social Security 
Minister Mehmet Mogultay, who is also acting as foreign 
minister, said on Tuesday [1 March] that Turkey will take 
initiatives to provide security for Palestinians. 
  Mogultay and Foreign Ministry Under Secretary Ozdem Sanberk 
visited the Palestinian Embassy in Ankara and signed a memorial 
book which was dedicated to the 63 Palestinian victims of the 
Ibrahim Mosque massacre in Hebron by a Jewish settler last 
Friday. 
  Mogultay expressed condolences to Palestinian Ambassador 
Fu'ad Yasin over the incident. 
  Yasin called for international protection for the 
Palestinians living in Israel. Israel and the PLO signed a 
treaty in Washington on Sept. 13, 1993 that provides autonomy 
for the Palestinians living in the Gaza strip and the city of 
Jericho. 
  Mogultay said Israel and the PLO should continue a 
constructive dialogue as the peace process is in a critical 
point. 
  He said a lasting and peaceful solution should be found to 
the problem. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

