<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Assembly Condemns Greek Decision on Pontus Anniversary </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0103193294 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1700 
GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0103193294 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Text] The Turkish Grand National Assembly [TGNA] has 
issued a statement condemning the Greek parliament's decision 
declaring 19 May as the anniversary of the so-called Pontus 
massacre. 
  The political party groups jointly drafted a statement 
drawing the attention of world public opinion. The statement, 
which was read out by Mustafa Kalemli during today's session, is 
as follows: 
  The declaration of 19 May, which marks the beginning of the 
Turkish liberation struggle, as the anniversary of the so-called 
Pontus massacre by the Greek parliament reflects an extremely 
dangerous and warped mentality. We regret and condemn this 
meaningless and baseless decision of the Greek parliament. 
  The Greek parliament appears to have forgotten that 75 years 
ago Greece attacked Anatolia with the aim of eradicating the 
Turkish nation. We would like to remind world public opinion of 
the tyranny and barbarism applied by occupying Greece against 
innocent people in Anatolia between 1919 and 1920. The actions 
undertaken by Greece in Anatolia in violation of the law on wars 
have been documented by the Lausanne Treaty, which is a 
multilateral international document. 
  Given this situation, it is evident that the fact that the 
Greek parliament is turning hostile attitudes against Turkey 
into a state policy by distorting historical facts will merely 
undermine bilateral relations and regional peace. We ask the 
Greek parliament to display intelligence and common sense. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

