<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Inter-European Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sweden's Dinkelspiel `Satisfied' With EU Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0103144794 Brussels BELGA in Dutch 1254 GMT 1 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0103144794 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels BELGA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Dutch </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed CET: "Sweden Agrees to Join EU"; as released </F>
by Brussels BELGA Database] 
  [Text] Brussels, 1 Mar (BELGA) -- Swedish European Affairs 
Minister Ulf Dinkelspiel said that he was satisfied with his 
country's agreement with the EU [European Union]. It is an 
historic day for Sweden, he added. 
  The agreement constitutes a good basis for carrying out the 
referendum on Sweden's accession to the EU, especially since the 
opposition was closely involved in the negotiations. 
  The minister reported that Sweden's net budget contribution 
will not exceed ECU50 million in the first year. Without the 
compensation, it would have amounted to about ECU760 million. 
  For the second year, Sweden's net budget contribution will 
rise to ECU150 million. The following year, the contribution 
will be significantly higher and by the fourth year, Sweden will 
have to pay its full contribution. 
  Dinkelspiel said that a couple of issues still remain to be 
settled. The Twelve have not reached an agreement regarding the 
voting procedure in the European Ministerial Council. Spain and 
the United Kingdom want to make it easier for large countries to 
block a decision. Furthermore, Spain does not want the new 
members to participate in the 1996 final settlement of the 
European Economic and Monetary Union (EMU). 
  The European Treaty envisages the third and last phase of 
the 
EMU starting in 1997 with the single currency and the European 
Central Bank, provided that a majority of the member states 
comply with the conditions. 
  Spain wants the treaty to be modified, clearly stating that 
all decisions must be made by a majority of the current 12 
member states. 
  Belgium and most member states have rejected the Spanish 
proposal. The issues have not been discussed so far, however. 
Thus, the position of the new member states in the future EMU is 
not clearly defined. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>
